article.headline: Shareef hits final three shots down the stretch
article.story:
ATLANTA (AP) -- Shareef Abdur-Rahim waited until crunch time to find his shooting touch. Abdur-Rahim made the most of his poor shooting night by hitting his last three shots in the final minutes to lead the Atlanta Hawks to a 75-70 victory over the Toronto Raptors on Saturday night. The Raptors played without leading scorer Vince Carter, who strained his right quadriceps in Thursday's 78-74 victory over New Orleans. "That helped. I'm not going to deny that," Atlanta coach Terry Stotts said. Abdur-Rahim led the Hawks with 20 points, but connected on only five of his first 20 shots before hitting three in the final 2:34. He finished 8-of-23 and scored 20 points with 12 rebounds. "For me, it really felt good because I was just struggling the whole night to make shots," Abdur-Rahim said. "I was trying to make something happen, and to make those shots deep in the game put them in a tough situation." With Atlanta clinging to a 64-63 lead, Abdur-Rahim made it 66-63 with a short jumper. He then hit two 15-footers, the final one 40.6 seconds left for a 70-65 margin. "He's been in the league long enough. I don't have to tell him anything," Stotts said. "He didn't turn down shots, and he had his confidence going to knock them down." The Raptors never got closer than three after that. Stephen Jackson added 19 points for the Hawks, hitting all four of his 3-pointers. Donyell Marshall led Toronto with 16 points. Alvin Williams had 15 and Jalen Rose had 13. "The team needed me to step up (with Vince out), and I let the team down," said Rose, who shot only 5-of-19. "Blame this loss on Jalen Rose." It wasn't just Rose. The Raptors shot only 37 percent from the field (27-of-74) and made only 11 of 22 free throws. "We didn't execute very well all night. We didn't do the things we needed to do to finish them off," Raptors coach Kevin O'Neill said. The Hawks led 16-8 after the first quarter, the second-lowest scoring quarter of the season for the Raptors. Toronto had only four points in the second quarter of an 86-60 loss to Washington on Nov. 7. The Hawks built a 13-point lead, 25-12, early in the second on a 3-pointer by Jackson. The Raptors tied it at 28 on a 3-pointer by Lamond Murray, but trailed 37-31 at the half.

Game notes
Rookie F Chris Bosh, the Raptors' No. 1 draft pick out of Georgia Tech, started after missing four games with a sprained right knee. He played 30 minutes and scored six points, but only was 2-of-9 from the free throw line. ... Atlanta F Alan Henderson missed the game, flying to Indianapolis to be with his mother, who was hospitalized. ... Seven of the Hawks' next eight games are at home.
